      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 9.0,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-NBB00.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.043
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "t_start": 0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 6,
      "narration_text": "Bohr's atom has the electron on a circle — one exact radius. But the electron's most likely radius and its average radius are different numbers.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "Why the Electron Has No Orbit, Only a Cloud",
        "kicker": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "style": "title"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.86,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/clips/B01.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B01.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "t_start": 6,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "In Bohr's model, the ground-state electron sits on a circle at the Bohr radius a₀ = 0.053 nm. One radius. Most probable equals average equals orbit radius.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.25,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/clips/B02.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "t_start": 16,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Quantum mechanics solves hydrogen exactly. The electron is a cloud. If most probable and average are the same, there might still be an orbit — but what if they differ?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "What if most probable ≠ average?",
        "style": "question"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.64,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/clips/B03.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "t_start": 25,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The radial probability density is P(r) = r² e^{−2r/a₀} times a constant. It starts at zero, peaks somewhere, then decays — not a spike at one radius.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.67,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/clips/B04.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "t_start": 35,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Where does P(r) peak? Take the derivative, set it to zero. The most probable radius is exactly a₀. Bohr's guess of a circle lands here — but that is the only thing he got right.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.83,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/clips/B05.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "t_start": 47,
      "estimated_duration_s": 4,
      "narration_text": "The mechanism: the distribution has a tail.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "The tail pulls the average past the peak.",
        "style": "section"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 2.4,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/clips/B06.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "t_start": 51,
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "P(r) has a long tail at large r. The average — the integral of r times P(r) — weighs the tail. The result: ⟨r⟩ = 3a₀/2, sitting beyond the peak at a₀.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.65,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/clips/B07.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B07.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "t_start": 64,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Two different numbers — a₀ for the peak, 1.5a₀ for the mean. A circle cannot do that. Two different numbers is the mathematical proof that there is no orbit.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.95,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/clips/B08.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B08.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "t_start": 75,
      "estimated_duration_s": 3,
      "narration_text": "An orbit would give one number. A cloud gives two.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "Orbit → one number. Cloud → two.",
        "style": "implication"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 3.16,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/clips/B09.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B09.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "t_start": 78,
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "The quantum cloud is spherically symmetric — no preferred direction. The 90%-probability isosurface is a sphere. No point in space is singled out as the position of the electron. There is no trajectory between measurements.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "STILL",
        "source": "ai",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
          "provenance": "proven-core/SlateCard",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "headline": "The quantum cloud is spherically symmetric — no preferred direction. The…",
            "eyebrow": "",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B10.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.87,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/clips/B10.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B10.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "t_start": 91,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Bohr got the energies right because a₀ is a real length scale in the exact solution. But the orbit is a fiction. The length scale is real. The circle is not.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.29,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/clips/B11.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B11.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "t_start": 103,
      "estimated_duration_s": 3,
      "narration_text": "The numbers: a₀ and 3a₀/2.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "Worked example",
        "style": "example"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 2.64,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/clips/B12.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B12.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B13",
      "t_start": 106,
      "estimated_duration_s": 20,
      "narration_text": "P(r) = (4/a₀³)r²e^{−2r/a₀}. Most probable: dP/dr = 0 → r_peak = a₀ = 0.053 nm. Average: ⟨r⟩ = integral of r·P dr from 0 to ∞ = 3a₀/2 = 0.079 nm. The gap between them is 0.026 nm — real, measurable in the wavefunction.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B13.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 23.72,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/clips/B13.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B13.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B14",
      "t_start": 126,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "What if the most probable and average radius differ? They do: a₀ for the peak, 3a₀/2 for the mean. That gap is the cloud. That gap is the end of the orbit. QUANTUM MECHANICS.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "The gap between peak and mean is the cloud.",
        "kicker": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "style": "recap"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B14.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.607,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/clips/B14.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-hydrogen-cloud/mp3/beat-B14.mp3"
    },
    {
